<DOC><DOCNO> AP880508-0086 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 2152EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-MarcosMemorial     05-08 0227</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Marcos Memorial,0233</SECOND><HEAD>Thousands Attend Memorial Service For Marcos' Mother</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Philippines</HEAD><DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 1,000 supporters gathered at thehillside estate of Ferdinand Marcos on Sunday for a three-hourmemorial service for the exiled Philippines president's mother.   ``A Philippines that is free, democratic and strong, that is thelegacy of my mother,'' Marcos said in the eulogy.   ``I shall not see her dead. I shall see her alive. She will bewith me every day of my life,'' said Marcos, who was deniedpermission to return to the Philippines for the funeral of JosefaEdralin-Marcos, who died there Wednesday.   Philippines President Corazon Aquino, in a radio broadcast inManila on Sunday, reiterated that she decided against allowingMarcos to return for security reasons.   The Roman Catholic service here, which included recitation ofthe burial rites, was held on the lawn of the Marcos home. A smallwhite tent was erected for the Marcos family and their closefriends.   Marcos' wife, Imelda, and the couple's daughter, Irene, bothsang, and several leaders of Marcos support groups spoke.   Following the service the supporters who were transported to theestate on tour buses were fed McDonald's hamburgers, spaghetti andtraditional Filipino foods.   Marcos and his family have lived here since fleeing Manila inFebruary 1986 during a largely non-violent uprising that broughtMrs. Aquino to power.</TEXT></DOC>